Demo 1: Reconstructing the Logistic Map

Rick Dale and Harish Bhat

5/31/2018

This brief code obtains a simulation of the simple but wonderful logistic map. Note that, as a discrete system, we take the derivative (dx) to be the system at the next time step. This was done in Brunton et al. (2016) and we do this here. See the text in Dale and Bhat for a discussion of discretely vs. continuously updated systems.

library(sindyr)
set.seed(666)

as = seq(from=2.1,to=3.99,by=.05) # the range of parameters used
xs = c()
x = runif(1)
for (a in as) {
  xs_temp = c()
  x = runif(1)
  for (i in 1:200) { # iterations per control parameter value
    x = a*x*(1-x)
    xs_temp = rbind(xs_temp,data.frame(a=a,x=x))
  }
  xs = rbind(xs,xs_temp)
}  
xs[1:4,]
##     a         x
## 1 2.1 0.3324863
## 2 2.1 0.4660722
## 3 2.1 0.5225827
## 4 2.1 0.5239290
dx = as.matrix(xs[2:nrow(xs),])
xs = xs[1:(nrow(xs)-1),]

sindy.obj = sindy(xs=xs,dx=dx) # build the SINDy object
sindy.obj$B # the fit
##                    a          x
## (Intercept) 0.000000  0.0000000
## a           1.000077  0.0000000
## x           0.000000  0.0000000
## a:a         0.000000  0.0000000
## a:x         0.000000  0.9975896
## x:x         0.000000  0.0000000
## a:a:a       0.000000  0.0000000
## a:a:x       0.000000  0.0000000
## a:x:x       0.000000 -0.9968673
## x:x:x       0.000000  0.0000000

For illustration of the system, we display the system values over the control parameter (a), along with the set of features used to reconstruct the logistic map with SINDy.

# 
# let's get some plots
#
par(mfrow=c(1,2))
plot(xs[xs$a==2.2,2],type='b',xlab='Iteration (t)',ylab='x',main='a = 2.2') # under values a=2.2
plot(xs[xs$a==3.95,2],type='b',xlab='Iteration (t)',ylab='x',main='a = 3.95') # under values a=3.95

par(mfrow=c(1,3))
plot(xs[,1],type='p',cex=.5,pch=15,xlab='t',ylab='a') # a
plot(xs[,2],type='p',cex=.5,pch=15,xlab='t',ylab='x') # x
plot(dx,type='p',cex=.5,pch=15,xlab='t',ylab='dx') # dx

Theta = features(xs,3) # grid of features
par(mfrow=c(3,3),oma = c(2,0,0,0) + 0.1,mar = c(1,1,1,1) + 0.1)
for (i in 2:ncol(Theta)) {
  plot(Theta[,i],xlab='t',main=gsub(':','',colnames(Theta)[i]),type='l',xaxt='n',yaxt='n')
}

#
# let's model the logistic under particular values
#
par(mfrow=c(1,2))
x.now = xs[xs$a==2.2,][1,]
xs_modeled = xs[xs$a==2.2,][1,]
for (i in 1:200) {
  x.now = features(x.now,3) %*% sindy.obj$B
  xs_modeled = rbind(xs_modeled,x.now)
}
plot(xs_modeled[,2],type='b',xlab='Iteration (t)',ylab='x',main='a = 2.2') # under values a=2.2

x.now = xs[xs$a==3.95,][1,]
xs_modeled = xs[xs$a==3.95,][1,]
for (i in 1:200) {
  x.now = features(x.now,3) %*% sindy.obj$B
  xs_modeled = rbind(xs_modeled,x.now)
}
plot(xs_modeled[,2],type='b',xlab='Iteration (t)',ylab='x',main='a = 3.95') # under values a=3.95
